{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5bf4eab1-0cf3-4b1b-9967-23f92b64ed9f","content":"These are two separate C# 15 breaking changes:\n\n---\n\n**1. `left && right` — dynamic + user-defined short-circuit operators**\n\n`&&` desugars to `IFilter.false(left) ? left : IFilter.&(left, right)`. The compiler finds `operator true`/`operator false` on `IFilter`, but `IFilter` doesn't define `operator &` — only `CompositeFilter` does. In earlier C# versions, the `dynamic` right operand caused the whole expression to be deferred to runtime binding, masking this mismatch. C# 15 now validates at compile time that the type providing `operator true`/`operator false` also provides `operator &`, even when the other operand is `dynamic`.\n\n**Fix options:**\n- Cast both to `dynamic`: `(dynamic)left && right`\n- Add `operator &` to `IFilter`\n- Use explicit two-step logic: `if (left) { combined = left & right; }`\n\n---\n\n**2. `ref readonly` lambda — CS0518**\n\n`ref readonly` return types on lambdas require the compiler to emit a `RefReadOnlyAttribute` (or similar metadata) on the synthesized delegate's `Invoke` return. CS0518 (\"predefined type is not defined or imported\") means the required well-known type isn't found in your referenced assemblies.\n\n**Fix options:**\n- Ensure you're targeting **net11.0** (not an older TFM with the new SDK)\n- Verify `System.Runtime` references are up to date\n- As a workaround, use a named delegate or method instead of a lambda:\n  ```csharp\n  delegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();\n  static ref readonly int GetValue() => ref value;\n  RefReadOnlyFunc fn = GetValue;\n  ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"47aa6c7f-f49d-4c84-bdb8-9dae5a96abae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both cases.\n\n**Case 1: `DynamicOps.cs` - `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a change related to how `&&` and `||` operators work with `dynamic` operands. The `&&` operator is a short-circuit operator that relies on `operator true`/`operator false` and `operator &`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler historically allowed this and resolved it at runtime. \n\n\nHowever, C# 15 now rejects this pattern because the compiler can't reliably determine at compile time how to handle short-circuiting when mixing static user-defined operators with dynamic resolution. The ambiguity arises from trying to coordinate the static `operator true`/`operator false` on the left operand's type with the dynamic resolution of `operator &` on the right side.\n\nTo fix this, I'd either cast the left operand to `dynamic` as well to make the entire expression dynamic, or restructure the code to avoid mixing static and dynamic operands in short-circuit operations.\n\nNow looking at the `RefHelper.cs` case with the `ref readonly` lambda - the CS0518 error suggests a predefined type isn't available, which points to a runtime compatibility issue with how C# 15 handles `ref readonly` return types on lambdas. For `ref readonly` return types on lambdas, the compiler needs to synthesize a delegate type that supports this, which likely requires a new well-known type or attribute in the runtime. The CS0518 error suggests the project isn't targeting .NET 11 or is missing the necessary runtime support that C# 15 now expects for this feature.\n\nLooking at the actual issues more carefully: the dynamic short-circuit operator problem stems from a conflict between statically resolving `operator true`/`operator false` and dynamically resolving `operator &`, which C# 15 appears to have tightened into an error. For `ref readonly` lambdas, the compiler needs to create an anonymous method with a `ref readonly` return type, which requires synthesizing a delegate—and CS0518 suggests the compiler is looking for a well-known type that doesn't exist in the referenced assemblies, likely because C# 15 introduced proper support for this feature and needs a new BCL type. is `IFilter`, the compiler can't resolve the `&&` operator because `IFilter` defines `operator true` and `operator false` but lacks `operator &`, while `operator &` only exists on the concrete `CompositeFilter` type. Since `right` is `dynamic`, the compiler can't determine which overload to use.\n\nIn C# 15, with static abstract operators now allowed in interfaces, the compiler might be enforcing stricter resolution rules for `&&` through the interface rather than falling back to dynamic resolution like it did before. The interface has the logical operators but not the bitwise `&`, so the compiler refuses to proceed. The second issue involves `ref readonly` return types on lambdas, which require the compiler to synthesize a compatible delegate type. The CS0518 error suggests a required BCL type for `ref readonly`-returning delegates isn't available—likely because C# 15 introduced or changed support for this feature, needing infrastructure that isn't present in the target framework. I'd need to verify the target framework is .NET 11 or use a named method instead.\n\nFor the `&&` operator issue, the core problem is that `&&` requires both `operator true/false` and `operator &` on the same type, and with `dynamic` involved, the resolution becomes complicated in C# 15's stricter type checking.","outputTokens":2826,"requestId":"681A:2ED2CA:2671113:2A673C2:69FD2A1A"},"id":"a3e8fed4-8267-453b-b6c4-a256e7869af6","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:12:05.636Z","parentId":"15669fbf-f571-4d5f-85d2-f5dfe42f8c4f"}
